description.narrative:
Helvetas, an international NGO, has developed a proposal covering the establishment of a regional inclusive economic development programme, where the main part of the budget (75%) is dedicated to regional level work Eastern Europe and a country window for Armenia. The remaining part is dedicated to Western Balkans including a small North Macedonia window. The intervention, amounting to 35 million SEK, is an inception- and pilot phase in preparation of two larger long term programmes in Eastern Europe and Western Balkans which are expected to start during spring 2022.
The intervention framework applies an inclusive market systems development approach where the inception phase consists of a set of deliverables relating to research, analysis, institution building and piloting of interventions for possible scale-up within a longer term programme. A number of local partners will be engaged in the implementation and Helvetas has the right to forward funds accordingly. The expected results are process targets relating to programme design and institutionalization, combined with some early outcome effects on employment and incomes (4,000 people) and improved employability (skills improvements for around 8,000 people).

Helvetas, en internationell enskild organisation, har utvecklat ett förslag på etablering av en regional sysselsättningsinsats, varav merparten avser landspecifikt arbete i Armenien, och regionalt arbete i Östeuropa (75%). Återstoden allokeras till arbete på Västra Balkan, inklusive ett litet landfönster för Nordmakedonien.
Insatsen uppgår till 35 miljoner SEK och omfattar 22 månaders inceptions- och pilotarbete för två större regionala program i Östeuropa och på Västra Balkan, med förväntad start under våren 2022.
Insatsen tillämpar en inkluderande marknadssystemansats och innevarande fas består av komponenter som forskning, analys, institutionsuppbyggnad och testning av en rad insatshypoteser för uppskalning i ett långsiktigt program. Ett antal internationella och lokala organisationer förväntas bidra till genomförandet, och Helvetas har rätt att vidareförmedla medel för detta ändamål. De förväntade resultaten är huvudsakligen processmål samt vissa effekter på sysselsättning och inkomstskapande (4 000 personer) och förbättrad anställningsbarhet (förbättrade yrkesrelaterade färdigheter för 8 000 personer).

The intervention is a research and piloting phase of a larger and longer term expected programme. As such, the majority of objectives relate to deliverables in research, piloting, institutionalization and long term design work as outlines in the Inception Plan section of the Proposal (Annex 7.2).
In addition to the output level deliverables referenced above, the pilot interventions envisioned for this phase is expected to yield some early development outcomes in themselves (Annex 7.1). The ultimate objectives of the longer term programme envisioned are improved incomes and employment opportunities for economically disadvantaged people. Women and youth are pre-defined as belonging to this group. A hypothetical assessment presented in the results framework attached to the Proposal, is that around 8,000 people's lives are likely to be affected by changes catalyzed by the project, out of which 4,000 will see explicit income improvements already during the course of the programme. An estimated CHF 3.3 million (SEK 33 million) are expected to be mobilized by the private sector towards the programme objectives.
With a cost extension for the programme which extends operations up to the end of 2022, the number of beneficiaries with improved employment opportunities are expected to increase by 1,800. The additional amount of private sector capital expected to be mobilized is CHF 1 million (SEK 10 million).

tag.narrative: 1.2 - By 2030, reduce at least by half the proportion of men, women and children of all ages living in poverty in all its dimensions according to national definitions.
1.2 - Till 2030 minst halvera den andel män, kvinnor och barn i alla åldrar som lever i någon form av fattigdom enligt nationella definitioner.

1.4 - By 2030, ensure that all men and women, in particular the poor and the vulnerable, have equal rights to economic resources, as well as access to basic services, ownership and control over land and other forms of property, inheritance, natural resources, appropriate new technology and financial services, including microfinance.

1.4 - Senast 2030 säkerställa att alla män och kvinnor, i synnerhet de fattiga och de utsatta, har lika rätt till ekonomiska resurser, tillgång till grundläggande tjänster, möjlighet att äga och kontrollera mark och andra former av egendom samt tillgång till arv, naturresurser, lämplig ny teknik och finansiella tjänster, inklusive mikrokrediter.

1.a - Ensure significant mobilization of resources from a variety of sources, including through enhanced development cooperation, in order to provide adequate and predictable means for developing countries, in particular least developed countries, to implement programmes and policies to end poverty in all its dimensions.

1.a - Säkra en betydande resursmobilisering från en mängd olika källor, inklusive genom ökat utvecklingssamarbete, i syfte att ge utvecklingsländerna, i synnerhet de minst utvecklade länderna, tillräckliga och förutsebara medel för att genomföra program och politik för att avskaffa all form av fattigdom.

1.b - Create sound policy frameworks at the national, regional and international levels, based on pro-poor and gender-sensitive development strategies, to support accelerated investment in poverty eradication actions.

1.b - Upprätta sunda policyramverk på nationell, regional och internationell nivå på grundval av utvecklingsstrategier som stödjer de fattiga och tar hänsyn till jämställdhetsaspekter, för att stödja ökade investeringar i åtgärder för att avskaffa fattigdom.

5.4 - Erkänna och värdesätta obetalt omsorgs- och hushållsarbete genom att tillhandahålla offentliga tjänster, infrastruktur och socialt skydd samt genom att främja delat ansvar inom hushållet och familjen, i enlighet med vad som är nationellt lämpligt.

5.4 - Recognize and value unpaid care and domestic work through the provision of public services, infrastructure and social protection policies and the promotion of shared responsibility within the household and the family as nationally appropriate.
5.5 - Ensure women’s full and effective participation and equal opportunities for leadership at all levels of decision-making in political, economic and public life.
5.5 - Tillförsäkra kvinnor fullt och faktiskt deltagande och lika möjligheter till ledarskap på alla beslutsnivåer i det politiska, ekonomiska och offentliga livet.
8.2 - Achieve higher levels of economic productivity through diversification, technological upgrading and innovation, including through a focus on high-value added and labour-intensive sectors.
8.2 - Uppnå högre ekonomisk produktivitet genom diversifiering, teknisk uppgradering och innovation, bland annat genom att fokusera på sektorer med högt förädlingsvärde och hög arbetsintensitet.

8.4 - Fram till 2030 successivt förbättra den globala resurseffektiviteten i konsumtionen och produktionen samt sträva efter att bryta sambandet mellan ekonomisk tillväxt och miljöförstöring, i enlighet med det tioåriga ramverket för hållbar konsumtion och produktion, med de utvecklade länderna i täten.

8.4 - Improve progressively, through 2030, global resource efficiency in consumption and production and endeavour to decouple economic growth from environmental degradation, in accordance with the 10-Year Framework of Programmes on Sustainable Consumption and Production, with developed countries taking the lead.
8.5 - By 2030, achieve full and productive employment and decent work for all women and men, including for young people and persons with disabilities, and equal pay for work of equal value.

8.5 - Senast 2030 uppnå full och produktiv sysselsättning med anständiga arbetsvillkor för alla kvinnor och män, inklusive ungdomar och personer med funktionsnedsättning, samt lika lön för likvärdigt arbete.
8.6 - By 2020, substantially reduce the proportion of youth not in employment, education or training.
8.6 - Till 2020 väsentligt minska den andel ungdomar som varken arbetar eller studerar.

description.narrative:
So far results can be seen on process level as well as development level. Below are a few snapshots, focusing on events and activities taken place during 2021. Overall performance. Reconomy´s management team have been extraordinarily committed, knowledgeable and responsive. They have successfully established a remarkably complex programme in an extremely difficult, variable and geographically diverse environment, where challenges have also been heavily exacerbated by Covid-19 and conflict dynamics. The Russian invasion of Ukraine has affected the implementation in all countries but to a different degree. Helvetas has submitted a scenario analysis of the programme and future possible programming obstacles and this will be discussed during the annual meeting end May 2022.
A programme organization has been put in place and fully staffed with a well-balanced team of committed and professional people. Half a dozen of pilot interventions have been designed and kicked off in an iterative process anchored in pre-existing and complementary market systems assessments (MSA). Partnerships with local implementers have been agreed for all the (five) pilot projects approved so far. Pilot partners express a high degree of satisfaction with the programme approach as well as value-additions and relationships with Helvetas and Reconomy staff. Helvetas has also supported Sida with a large number of high quality inputs and second opinions of various institutions and initiatives in the region. This has allowed Sida to perform even better in multi-stakeholder consultations and external programme design. They have also held a large number of capacity building events on the topic of inclusive systemic programming for partners and Sida colleagues in the regions. (See progress reports and related statements for more information.)
Challenges encountered were overall expected since the MSD approach with inclusive systemic programming hasn´t been comprehensively tested at regional level before. Additionally, Helvetas have more experiences and networks on the Western Balkans than in Eastern Europe where Reconomy (including the Armenia window) has 2/3 of their operations. The wide geographical coverage of Reconomy also solicited establishment of new institutional modes of operation for Helvetas, creating a somewhat unpredictable period of institutionalization over the past year. Covid-19 and outbreak of war in Armenia delayed the initial round of market systems assessments, when researchers couldn´t operate as usual given mobility restrictions in and between countries.
The work on consolidating the establishment of a MRM (Monitoring and Results Measurement) system continued, for example by developing an IT-solution and strengthening the coordination inhouse between the MRM and the KMLC (Knowledge Management Learning and Communication). One example of consolidation is that processes to conduct and review pilot interventions were introduced.
The structure and processes for managing the financial aspects of the programme and ensuring cost efficient use of funds was further strengthened during 2021. The budget utiliazation rate Jan - Dec 2021 was 78% and the use of funds of implementing partners of Helvetas was improved.
Eastern Partnership region: Results include successfully advocating and facilitiating the adoption of ten regulations by local authorities and signing of a memo on cooperation with Economic Expert Platform form Ukraine, this strenghtening the public - private dialogue. In Moldova the national legislation in the regulatory sphere was assessed and analysed in a research paper.
In Moldova the pilot on employment opportunites in the textile and apparel sector addressed employability by the accelaration intiative which focuses on developing successfull business models and training sessions to increase sales.
Challenges are linked to outdated skills systems, male dominated business environment as well as low capacity of third parties.
Armenia: Overall, the pilots in Armenia has progressed well, all things considered. There are still challenges in relation to covid-effects as well as the post-conflict tension with Azerbaijan, and these challenges has had an impact on some vulnerabl regions such as Syunik and Gegharkunik provinces.
The work within the textile and apparel sector has included the development of training curriculums by engaging market actors as well as the development of a concept for public awareness of Armenian brands and companies through collaboration between key actors. There have been some challenges regarding the lack of clarity on roles and responsibilities in this pilot.
In "Energy Transition for Income and Employment" a new market actor - LLC Rubinar (PV systems import, trader, and installer) has been identified and engaged in the pilot project implementation and will partner with earlier identified NGO Ferti, which runs training programs for youth in RE & EE technologies. They have started the identification of training participants among the youth in two regions of Armenia.
Most progress has however been made in the third pilot "Skills, knowledge & intermediation development" with a number of activities and trainings in the identified sectors, agribusiness/agriculture and tourism/hospitality. In particular it is worth mentioning the cooperation with Armenian National Agrarian University who among other things opened a Teaching-Experimental Farm Training?Center?for?dairy products with support from RECONOMY.
Western Balkans region: The Western Balkan pilot Vibrant service sector for better economic opportunities covering Serbia, Kosovo, Montenegro and North Macedonia continued market system analysis and finetuned designed as well as showing promising results. Two assessments to finetune the pilot activities was conducted: 1) An analysis of the ICT sector in all countries in the region was conducted to identify relevant stakeholders, and 2) A market systems analysis of the needs and demands of the target group. Some targets are already achieved by far while others still need some work. Results include the initation of three new partnerships,
North Macedonia: The two pilot projects, in waste management and self-employment through freelancing, progressed well although the start was somewhat delayed for various reasons (mainly Covid and administrative delays). One example of a result achieved through advocacy and improved public-private dialogue is the collaboration with municipalities in the waste management pilot (p. 6). REDI, the social entrepreneur, signed a Memorandum of Understanding with two municipalities in Skopje, Aerodrom and Karposh, setting the basis for collaboration and support from the municipalities to provide a space for the temporary storage of collected waste materials. Also, a system for primary waste separation was established in 105 buildings in Skopje, another 253 have applied and systems have been procured but had not yet been established by the end of 2021 (p. 17). Regarding the other pilot project, self-employment through freelancing with Impact Foundation as the implementing partner, RECONOMY provided support in access to knowledge, people and target groups. One example of an activity carried out was that 154 people (92 women and 62 men) went through eight different training packages for three months and learned new digital skills and freelancing. 32 students managed to get a paid task and received incomes for their completed digital job (p. 18)
Risk management. Risk analysis and mitigation need to be deepened and closely monitored during 2022, not least relating to the effects of teh Russian invasion of Ukraine for the possibililty to scale up and enter into a possible main phase.
No indicator available - only a description of the activity results is published
